Statement of Work

Overview

This presentation is a data analytics capstone project using the fictitious company, Cyclistic Bike Share (Cyclistic).
Cyclistic is a bike sharing company that provides almost 6,000 bikes to the local community through some 600 stations
located throughout the greater Chicago area providing easy access to to several types of bicycles
including reclining, tricycles, and even cargo bikes. With the broad range of bicycles available, Cyclistic has
offerings that provides access to not only regular riders, but riders with disabilities, riders who need to transport
items and riders that prefer recumbent bikes.
Cyclistic asserts that the majority of riders opt for traditional bikes and about 8% use assistive bike options.
Cyclistic also believes that most of their customers are leisure riders rather than commuters which
they state is about 30% of their user base.
Marketing management’s focus is on promoting Cyclistic’s service and increasing membership with Cyclistic. The
marketing team is looking for analysis and recommendations on the following:

1. How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?
2. Why would casual riders buy Cyclistic annual memberships?
3. How can Cyclistic use digital media to influence casual riders to become members?

This analysis focuses on discovering how casual and members use Cyclistic bikes differently. An explanation of
steps taken to clean the data made available and some additional findings can be found in the appendix as the process
was complex due to the volume of data, the extensive steps necessary to validate and clean it, and the significant
deficiencies in the data provided.
My initial review of the data found numerous problems. In a real world engagement, I would normally have been able
to address these deficiencies. For instance, no information was provided on existing membership numbers. I also
found that the GPS data provided, seemed to track the physical location of the bike storage at level more granular
than the bike storage facilities, if it was provided at all, and for the reporting periods in question, the type of
bike used information for 2019 is non-existent. This made determining more refined member usage, geographic
routing usage, equipment type preferences problematic At this point, left primarily with usage date and times,
that is the significant information upon which reliable analysis was performed.

In my opinion, the there was much left on the table that could be discovered on how member and casual riders use Cyclistic
equipment.

——————————————————————————

Data preparation and cleaning

The data was received in a commonly used text format, comma separated. This data was broken up into quarterly or monthly
chunks, depending on the whim of the provider. Depending upon the size of the data, initial cleaning and analysis could be
handled using spreadsheets, text editors, or more robust tools. Due to the size of some of the files, spreadsheet tools
did not have the capability to allow for review all of the data in some of the files. Because of this, SQL Server was chosen
as the means of cleaning, analyzing and presentation resource. A free BigData account would not be capable of storing

the large data sets. In a traditional engagement, I would have used client resources, in this scenario, I maintained
the data locally on private systems not accessible by the Internet for security and isolation. It should be noted
that the data is available publicly and a link has been provided in the appendix.
Due to the size of the data and the need to load the large volume of data, over 7 million for 2019 and 2020, over
33 million records between 2019 and March of 2025, and some of the text files contained not easily observed artifacts
like missing carriage returns and lines, and Unix formatting as opposed to more traditional formats like UTF-8, a commonly
used encoding that is compatible with Unicode, an international encoding standard for use with different languages and
scripts, by which each letter, digit, or symbol is assigned a unique numeric value that applies across different platforms
and programs some programmatic formatting was required prior to bulk loading the raw data into a main cleaning table and a
a staging table used to allow for transformation prior to transfer into the main cleaning table. To address the formatting
issues Python was used to add some additional columns required by the analysis, and to normalize the file format across all
of the received data into new files formatted for bulk import into SQL Server. This left the original files pristine and
was used to produce properly formatted files with the same structure as the receiving SQL server tables that were easy to
bulk load via SQL Server programming functionality.

Once the source text files were loaded into the an SQL Server database, I proceeded to analyze the data for completeness
and validity. A detailed explanation of the methods used to find bad records and clean them out of the primary table
and retaining backups of the removed records for critical review for any concerns about cleaning steps taken are in
the appendix located later in this document for an in depth review of the entire data collection and cleaning process for
those who may wish to evaluate or question any process or steps taken to clean and validate the data.

This presentation was generated using Python, Microsoft SQL Server, R, andR Markdown language.

——————————————————————————

Analysis and Findings

Initial review of the data would lead one to believe that there are many answers to the question of how Cyclistic’s
customers use the service provided until a closer evaluation of the data is undertaken; duplicates, omissions, and
corrupt records abound in the raw data. Everything from no information about equipment types for 2019 not existing at
all to events ending before they started. No hard data about membership numbers over time were provided for analysis
leaving potentially useful analysis untapped. GPS information that alluded to station locations turned out to be more
granular, possibly pointing to actual storage slots rather than station location thus making traffic patterns analysis
unavailable for insightful analysis. Another unanswered question noted was the overview provided by the study that
stated there were some 600 locations where the bike are stored, but distinct searching of the start/end station ID records
found 1,236 distinct location identifiers for the years 2019 and 2020 More when querying across 2019 to 2024. There was
no avenue to validate this information or request clarification.
Since this project was a capstone lab project, Extending the process into potentially linking to publicly available
resources such as Open Address, US Census Bureau, or a commercial API are beyond the scope of this analysis but not the
capabilities of the author.

Given the constraints of the data and the assignment, the analysis below provides usage counts by customer type (casual or
member), over time frames (annual, quartely, monthly, weekly, hourly). Some visibility into customer usage by equipment
type is provided for 2020, with 2019 usage relegated to “Not provided” to at least provide a visual if no insight, and stay
within the parameters of the assigned analysis. In the real world, I would hope to address this types of problems with the
data to address the deficiencies and establish a solution. When considering methods for potentially addressing the missing
data, I determined that deleting or imputing the data for 2019 wasn’t a viable solution as it would have meant deleting the
entire 2019 data set just for a single missing element. I briefly considered K-Nearest Neighbor imputation to fabricate
proximate nearest values, but this type of solution would have been complex and computationally intensive to come up with
the KNN values for over 3 million records.

Average Ride Lengths

Both membership and casual riders on average ride for short periods of time but, casual members ride marginally longer
than members. Members on average tend to ride ten to fifteen minutes which indicates task oriented like last mile transport
to work or home. Casual riders on average ride about 30 to 45 minutes, a bit longer than members. Both members and casual
users ride Monday through Friday, and slightly longer on the weekends. Both casual and member riders ride seven days a
week. The drop in member ridership is significant in 2020, the pandemic’s impact not only on commerce and trade but
mortality should be considered when evaluating the decrease in numbers. This is not to state that either type of rider only rode within the narrow band the charting indicates upon initial review. This chart shows just the averages.

Average Daily Ridership

Average daily ridership was calculated across 2019 and 2020 and they indicate that casual riders are primarily weekend
riders that do use bikes during the week and members are heavy weekday riders but they are also consistent weekend riders.
each group was still consistent with membership usage highest Mondays through Fridays in 2019, and casual ridership
was still consistently heavier from Friday through Sunday. In 2020, members didn’t ride as much across the board but,
they tended ride more on the weekends consistently in 2020. Casual riders increased their ridership and the duration of
their rides.

Conclusions and Recommendations

In conclusion, members tend to ride for short periods of time and they ride consistently 7 days a week.
Casual riders ride mostly on the weekends but they also ride throughout the week, just not at the volumes
that members do. Electric bike use seems more popular with casual riders than members but the bulk of riders
ride the docked bike styles. This is probably due to the fact that docked bike are the most prevelant of the
types of bikes available.

There are several avenues for improvement in the data collection process that would make this data set more
valuable. For instance, cleaning up the GPS data by using the station name address GPS coordinates that are not
provided available as the sole GP coordinates for each station. Information about existing membership numbers over
time would provide better insight into membership usage statistics.

Depending on the size of the advertising budget; targeted advertising on trains, in and around bike facilities where
casual usage is greater might garner additional memberships with discounts and promotions for membership. The top 20,
departure stations would be good pilot campaign sites including including train and bus routes servicing these stations.

The next section of this presentation discusses analysis of the data beyond 2020 and how the data itself was
stored, cleaned and analyzed.

Data Collection, Preparation, Transformation, and Cleaning

SQL Server was chosen as the means to store, clean and run preliminary analysis on the data due to the volume, over
over 7 million for 2019 and 2020 alone and over 33 million from 2019 through to March of 2025. a cloud based DBMS tool
would have been cost prohibitive as compared to locally maintained infrastructure. Additionally, commonly used spread-
sheet tools like Excle and Google Sheets had difficulty handling some of the large file extracts provided. Text tools
like TextPad and NotePad+++ could have peformed some of the preliminary work but those tools are slow when dealing with
record set sizes encountered in this study.
in .csv files in a more robust database management system.
Here is a link to the raw data: [Cyclistic Data files] (https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html)
While spreadsheets and professional text editors like TextPad and Notepad+++ are great for initial data cleaning,
some of the data files were too large for Excel and even though Google Sheets could open them, it became unstable.
TextPad and NotePad+++ would have been adequte to modify a few .CSV files, but even using macros, mask changes to
the .CSV was time prohibitive. To address this, Python scripts were used to perform mass changes on the files,
not only only adding two new columns with blank data, but confirming that the files were formatted with carriage
returns and line feeds so that the the bulk load process would perform successfully.

## CREATE VIEW [dbo].[divvy_bad_trip_counts_by_period_vw]

##      WHEN 4 THEN '02' WHEN 5 THEN '02' WHEN 6 THEN '02'

##  CASE MONTH(started_at) WHEN 1 THEN '01' WHEN 2 THEN '01' WHEN 3 THEN '01'

##      WHEN 7 THEN '03' WHEN 8 THEN '03' WHEN 9 THEN '03'

Create view divvy_mbr_pct_cas_vw 

## Skipping Creation of divvy_bad_trip_counts_by_period_vw view.
## SQL code:
##  
## /****** Object:  View [dbo].[divvy_mbr_pct_cas_vw]    Script Date: 5/19/2025 1:55:26 PM ******/
## DROP VIEW [dbo].[divvy_mbr_pct_cas_vw]
## GO
## 
## /****** Object:  View [dbo].[divvy_mbr_pct_cas_vw]    Script Date: 5/19/2025 1:55:26 PM ******/
## SET ANSI_NULLS ON
## GO
## 
## SET QUOTED_IDENTIFIER ON
## GO
## 
## CREATE   VIEW [dbo].[divvy_mbr_pct_cas_vw]
## AS
## SELECT TOP (100) PERCENT period_yr
##  , ROUND(CAST(casual_ride_count AS FLOAT),0) AS casual_ride_count
##  , ROUND(CAST(member_ride_count AS FLOAT),0)AS member_ride_count
##  , ROUND(CAST(total_ride_count AS FLOAT),0) AS total_ride_count
##  , CASE WHEN member_ride_count > 0 THEN 
##      CAST(ROUND(CAST(member_ride_count AS FLOAT) / total_ride_count * 100, 2) AS VARCHAR(10)) + '%'
##          ELSE NULL END AS member_as_percent_of_total
##  , CASE WHEN casual_ride_count > 0 THEN 
##      CAST(ROUND(CAST(casual_ride_count AS FLOAT) / total_ride_count * 100, 2) AS VARCHAR(10)) + '%'
##          ELSE NULL END AS casual_as_percent_of_total
## FROM (
##      SELECT c1.period_yr
##      , t2.total_ride_count
##      , SUM(CASE WHEN customer_type = 'casual' THEN ride_count ELSE 0 END) AS casual_ride_count
##      , SUM(CASE WHEN customer_type = 'member' THEN ride_count ELSE 0 END) AS member_ride_count
##      FROM (
##              SELECT YEAR(started_at) AS period_yr
##                  , member_casual AS customer_type
##                  , COUNT(ride_id) AS ride_count
##                 FROM            dbo.[divvy-tripdata] t1
##                 WHERE        (YEAR(started_at) < 2025)
##                 GROUP BY YEAR(started_at), member_casual
##          ) AS c1
##          LEFT JOIN (select YEAR(started_at) AS period_yr, COUNT(ride_id) AS total_ride_count FROM [dbo].[divvy-tripdata] GROUP BY YEAR(started_at)
##                                  ) t2 ON c1.period_yr = t2.period_yr
##              GROUP BY c1.period_yr, t2.total_ride_count
##      ) AS final
## ORDER BY period_yr
## GO

import csv
import re
import os
from pathlib import Path

# === Helper Function Definitions ===

def clean_numeric_field(value):
    """Remove commas from numeric fields."""
    if re.fullmatch(r'\d{1,3}(,\d{3})*(\.\d+)?', value):
        return value.replace(',', '')
    return value

def process_csv(input_file, output_file):
    """Clean numeric fields and add extra columns."""
    if not os.path.exists(input_file):
        print(f"Input file not found: {input_file}")
        return

    with open(input_file, 'r', encoding='utf-8', newline='') as infile, \
         open(output_file, 'w', encoding='utf-8', newline='\n') as outfile:

        reader = csv.reader(infile, delimiter=',', quotechar='"')
        writer = csv.writer(outfile, delimiter=',', quotechar='"', quoting=csv.QUOTE_MINIMAL)

        headers = next(reader)
        headers += ['ride_length', 'day_of_week']
        writer.writerow(headers)

        line_count = 0
        for row in reader:
            cleaned_row = [clean_numeric_field(field) for field in row]
            cleaned_row += ['', '']
            writer.writerow(cleaned_row)
            line_count += 1

        print(f"Processed {line_count} rows. Output saved to: {output_file}")

# === Batch Processing ===

Load files into tables

The SQL query that loads the .CSV files into the tables using CURSORS and makes calls
to the disk subsystem which uses file system calls that include back slashes in the
file paths which r interprets as code in R YAML.
Due to this, the process was converted to a stored procedure.
I encountered data problems with the data that were collected near the end of 2024 to
March of 2025; it would seem that some form of data collection paradigm shift occurred
in June of 2024.

divvy-tripdata records
CSV files with YYYYMM-divvy-tripdata naming convention that have valid dates import
into the gdac.dbo.divvy-tripdata table without issue. Additionally, the 2020 quarterly
file also imports into the divvy-tripdata table without transformation.
The process use the SQL “BULK INSERT” function to load the .CSV files leverage the CURSOR
function to iterate through a list of files to import. Due to the volume of data provided
for this lab assignment, over 30 million records as of this writing, the process takes
quite a bit of time depending on your disk subsystem, processor speed and RAM.

divvy_xxxx_qx records CSV files containing 2019 data by quarter required additionally data transformation due
to differences in column layouts and missing columns.
Files with the naming convention Divvy_Trips_2019_Qx.csv must be loaded into a
staging table, transformed prior to insertion into gdac.dbo.divvy-trips_xxxx_qx after
they have been modified using python to add two new columns, ride_length and day_of_week,
stripping out commas from numerical values encapsulated by double quotes, and adding two
commas at the end of each data line to create the new field data placeholders. Again,
while I could manually import the data, this was inefficient; I needed a quicker and more
streamline method. On top of that, Excel could not open the larger quarterly files for
manipulation without data loss.
Using the fore mentioned xml format file, the import of these files is facilitate by a
separate query process built into the stored procedure to facilitate this. the stored
procedure contains flags to allow for import of all or specific .CSV file sets
